Undid revision 808312385 by [[Special:Contributions/Thenabster126|Thenabster126]] ([[User talk:Thenabster126|talk]]) "Semite" is an archaic biblical term that denotes only a grouping of languages, not peoples.

/Ā/ is not the sound in "Aturaye." Ā denotes a long sound, while the first "a" in "Aturaye" is short and pronounced as "aw." As far as the related groups section, I posted a few sources regarding Armenians and didn't get any disagreement or feedback.

I don't know how many times I need to explain this, but "ē" is NOT the sound being represented in Suraye/Suryoye/Aturaye. Furthermore, Assyrians are more culturally and genetically similar to Armenians than the majority of Mizrahi Jews, so stop removing.

Stop changing the vowels in the transliteration of the name. They have already been explained to be wrong. Also, stop removing Armenians, as it was already explained that they are related to Assyrians before.
/* Music */ Cleaned up the music section a bit. Can still use some improvement.

The only vowel in any of these transliterations that can be indicated with the "long sound" is the "o" in "Suryoye". The rest of the vowels are not pronounced as "ae" for "a", "ee" for "e", and "yoo" for "u", so please stop adding them back.
The stress symbols being added to Suraye, Suryoye, and Aturaye are not correct. Please stop adding them back.
Orthography didn't make sense. Adjusted so it does.

"Aramaye" is not used by Eastern Assyrians, as I already stated. The Aramean identifier is solely found in West Assyrians, ergo "Aramaye" is never used to refer to a person.
"Aramaye" is NOT used at all in Eastern dialects. Stop adding it. It doesn't even mean "Assyrian."
